<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A141BE10FD6EF740" box="[554,699,1386,1407]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Cactus opuntia</emphasis>
<collectionCode id="7FD1AE6EFF96FFF7A1A9BE10FD06F740" box="[706,723,1386,1407]" country="Netherlands" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15678" name="Nationaal Herbarium Nederland, Leiden University branch" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" type="Herbarium">L</collectionCode>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF96FFF7A3E3BED4FBBCF7D2" blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A3E3BED4FEBBF7F7" bold="true" box="[136,366,1454,1480]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Species richness:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF96FFF7A205BED5FE1FF7F6" authorityName="Miller" authorityYear="1754" box="[366,458,1455,1481]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A205BED5FE1FF7F6" box="[366,458,1455,1481]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Opuntia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a genus with wide geographic distribution and comprises approximately 200 species. In 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF96FFF7A3CDBEA8FF38F7D3" box="[166,237,1490,1516]" name="Brazil" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, there are 5 species of which ocurr in 
<collectingRegion id="DB04F849FF96FFF7A1FDBEA8FCB2F7D3" box="[662,871,1490,1516]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF96FFF7A01DBEA8FB88F7D2" author="Carneiro, A. M. &amp; Farias-Singer, R. &amp; Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D." box="[886,1117,1490,1517]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" refId="ref8113" refString="Carneiro, A. M., Farias-Singer, R., Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D. (2016) Cactos do Rio Grande do Sul. Fundacao Zoobotanica do Rio Grande do Sul, Porto Alegre, 224 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Carneiro 
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A08ABEA9FBCCF7D3" box="[993,1049,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF96FFF7A3D6BE8CFE6CF40A" blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A3D6BE8CFE0DF42F" bold="true" box="[189,472,1526,1552]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">General distribution:—</emphasis>
The genus occurs from southern 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF96FFF7A02CBE8CFC4EF42F" box="[839,923,1526,1552]" name="Canada" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Canada</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF96FFF7A0D4BE8DFBF7F42E" box="[959,1058,1527,1553]" name="Uruguay" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
, with the largest number of species in 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF96FFF7A3CEBD60FF2EF40B" box="[165,251,1562,1588]" name="Mexico" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF96FFF7A262BD60FE7BF40A" author="Kiesling, R." box="[265,430,1562,1589]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" pagination="441 - 444" refId="ref8728" refString="Kiesling, R. (2005) Cactaceae. In: Burkart, A. &amp; Bacigalupo, N. (Eds.) Flora ilustrada de Entre Rios - Argentina, Tomo IV, Parte IV. Coleccion Cientifica del I. N. T. A, Buenos Aires, pp. 441 - 444." type="book chapter" year="2005">Kiesling 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="51DA6520FF96FFF7A3D6BD44FE59F4D7" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF96FFF7A3D6BD44FBFFF443" blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A3D6BD44FD11F467" bold="true" box="[189,708,1598,1624]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Distribution in Santa Maria river basin:—</emphasis>
In SMRB only 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF96FFF7A013BD45FA7EF467" authority="Arechavaletae (1905: 42)" authorityName="Arechavaletae" authorityPageNumber="42" authorityYear="1905" box="[888,1451,1598,1625]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="8" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="megapotamica">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A013BD45FB57F467" box="[888,1154,1599,1625]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Opuntia megapotamica</emphasis>
Arechavaletae (1905: 42)
</taxonomicName>
occurs (
<figureCitation id="81FB2A2EFF96FFF7A38BBD18FEECF443" box="[224,313,1634,1660]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415615/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
) and it has a wide distribution in fields, rocky outcrops and woods.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF96FFF7A3D6BDFCFE59F4D7" blockId="8.[136,1452,1454,1768]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF96FFF7A3D6BDFCFE15F49F" bold="true" box="[189,448,1670,1696]" pageId="8" pageNumber="161">Morphologic notes:—</emphasis>
The species is characterized by its shrub or arboreal size, with articulated branches, acicular thorns and usually diurnal orange or yellow flowers with fleshy fruits. It blooms from October to March, bearing fruit shortly after flowering.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
